@startuml "Main Event Loop with Periodic Job Checking"
title "Main Event Loop: Periodic Background Job Monitoring (JOB_CHECK_INTERVAL = 250ms)"

' ==================== CONSTANTS ====================

note as ConstantsNote
  **Timing Constants**
  - JOB_CHECK_INTERVAL = Duration::from_millis(250)
  - Event Poll Timeout = Duration::from_millis(50)
  - Main Loop Timeout = Duration::from_millis(100)
end note

' ==================== MAIN EVENT LOOP FLOW ====================

start

note on link
  Initialize:
  - last_job_check = Instant::now()
  - Spawn background event poller
  - Create mpsc channel for events
end note

:Initialize last_job_check: Instant;
:Spawn background event poller task;
:Create event_rx: mpsc::Receiver<TerminalEvent>;

partition "Main Event Loop" {
  repeat
    note on link
      **Receive Event with Timeout**
      Uses tokio::select! to handle:
      1. Incoming events from poller
      2. Timeout (100ms) for periodic checks
    end note

    split
      :Receive event from channel;
      note on link
        Path 1: Event arrived from poller
      end note

      if (Event == CtrlC?) then (YES)
        :Log "Ctrl+C detected"\n⚠ Cancel current token\n(for async interruption);
      endif

      :Store event;
      note on link
        Event stored for handling
      end note
    split again
      :Timeout triggered (100ms);
      note on link
        Path 2: No event, timeout fired
        Typical during idle/pause periods
      end note

      :Check if elapsed >= JOB_CHECK_INTERVAL;
      if (last_job_check.elapsed()\n>= JOB_CHECK_INTERVAL?) then (YES)
        floating note
          **Periodic Job Check Triggered**
          After 250ms of inactivity
        end note
        :call check_completed_jobs();
        :Update last_job_check = Instant::now();
        :Render UI;
      else (NO)
        :Continue loop;
      endif
      :skip to next iteration;
    end split

    if (Event exists?) then (YES)
      note on link
        **Handle Event**
        Process user input or system event
      end note

      if (Quit event?) then (YES)
        :Cancel ongoing operations;
        :Return false (exit);
        stop
      else (NO)
        :Delegate to handle_event(event);
      endif

      note on link
        **Check Jobs After Event**
        Reduces lock contention by batching checks
      end note

      :Check if elapsed >= JOB_CHECK_INTERVAL;
      if (last_job_check.elapsed()\n>= JOB_CHECK_INTERVAL?) then (YES)
        floating note
          **Periodic Job Check After Event**
          If 250ms elapsed since last check
        end note
        :call check_completed_jobs();
        :Update last_job_check = Instant::now();
      else (NO)
        note on link
          Not yet, skip job check
          Continue without lock contention
        end note
      endif

      :Render UI;
    else (NO)
      note on link
        Timeout occurred without event
        (handled in timeout branch above)
      end note
    endif

  until (Exit requested?)
}

:Display goodbye message;
:Clean up resources;
stop

' ==================== CHECK_COMPLETED_JOBS DETAIL ====================

note as CheckCompletedJobsNote
  **check_completed_jobs() Implementation**

  This function is called periodically (every 250ms+).
  It implements fail-fast lock poisoning pattern.

  **Pseudocode:**
  fn check_completed_jobs(&mut self) {
    // Fast path: read lock only
    let has_jobs = match self.job_manager.read() {
      Ok(guard) => guard.has_running_jobs(),
      Err(_poisoned) => {
        log::error!("Lock poisoned in read phase");
        return;  // FAIL-FAST: exit early
      }
    };

    if !has_jobs { return; }  // No jobs, skip expensive write lock

    // Only if jobs exist: acquire write lock
    let completed = match self.job_manager.write() {
      Ok(mut guard) => guard.check_completed(),
      Err(_poisoned) => {
        log::error!("Lock poisoned in write phase");
        return;  // FAIL-FAST: exit early
      }
    };

    // Display notifications for completed jobs
    for job in completed {
      state.add_output(format!("[{}] Done ({}) {}", job.id, exit_info, job.command));
    }
  }

  **Key Points**
  1. Two-phase locking: read first, then write if needed
  2. No lock recovery - fail-fast on poisoning
  3. Early return when no jobs exist (fast path)
  4. Periodic call (every 250ms) reduces contention
end note

' ==================== TIMELINE VISUALIZATION ====================

note as TimelineNote
  **Event Loop Timing Example**

  t=0ms    : Start loop iteration
  t=50ms   : Poll event (timeout 50ms) → No event
  t=100ms  : Main loop timeout → Trigger check if elapsed >= 250ms
  t=250ms  : elapsed() >= JOB_CHECK_INTERVAL → Check jobs
  t=260ms  : User types 'l'
  t=270ms  : Poll event → InputChar('l')
  t=275ms  : Handle event → update state
  t=280ms  : Check elapsed (only 30ms) → Skip job check
  t=290ms  : Render UI
  t=300ms  : Poll event → More user input
  t=310ms  : Handle event
  t=320ms  : Check elapsed (70ms) → Skip
  t=330ms  : Poll event (timeout 50ms) → No event
  t=380ms  : Main loop timeout → Check elapsed (130ms) → Skip
  t=430ms  : Main loop timeout → Check elapsed (180ms) → Skip
  t=480ms  : Main loop timeout → Check elapsed (230ms) → Still skip (not >= 250)
  t=500ms  : Poll event → ??? or timeout?
  t=510ms  : Main loop timeout → Check elapsed (260ms) >= 250ms → CHECK JOBS!
  t=520ms  : Update last_job_check = Instant::now()

  **Result**
  - Job checks happen ~every 250ms even during active typing
  - Fast paths and early returns minimize lock contention
  - UI stays responsive (<5ms typical frame time)
  - Job completion notifications within 250ms of actual completion
end note

@enduml
